You can achieve this using different methods.

# whereHas relation
Retrieving posts with a `whereHas` relation instead of first retrieving the tags will result in you only having to loop through one single unique array.

```php
$posts = Posts::whereHas(&#39;tags&#39;, function (Builder $query) {
    $query-&gt;whereIn(&#39;id&#39;, Auth::user()-&gt;tags-&gt;pluck(&#39;id&#39;)-&gt;toArray());
});
```

Now you are only selecting the actual posts without receiving the unnecessary tags first.

You can read about querying relationships in the [Laravel documentation.][1]

# &quot;Through&quot;-relations

Laravel also provides a convenient (yeah) way to query this by defining an additional relationship of the type _has many through_.

```php
/**
 * Get all of the tagged posts for this user
 */
public function taggedPosts()
{
   return $this-&gt;hasManyThrough(&#39;App\Post&#39;, &#39;App\Tag&#39;);
}
``` 

You must define this in the User model (probably User.php).

Now you can simply loop through `Auth::user()-&gt;taggedPosts`, e.g.
```php
@foreach (Auth::user()-&gt;taggedPosts as $post)
{{ $post-&gt;title }}
@endforeach
```

Read more in the [Laravel documentation.][2]


  [1]: https://laravel.com/docs/5.8/eloquent-relationships#querying-relationship-existence
  [2]: https://laravel.com/docs/5.8/eloquent-relationships#has-many-through

